.TH phoenixdkim-testkey 8 "PhoenixDKIM"
.SH NAME
.B phoenixdkim-testkey
\- DKIM filter installation test
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B phoenixdkim-testkey
[\-d domain] [\-s selector] [\-k keypath] [\-v] [\-x configfile]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B phoenixdkim-testkey
verifies the setup of signing and verifying (private and public) keys for use
with
.I phoenixdkim(8).

The test program will read a domain name and selector from the command
line, configuration file or a key table, then query and parse the resulting
DKIM key(s), reporting any errors found.

If a key path is also provided, the test program will read the private key
named and attempt to confirm that the private key specified by
.I keypath
(or in the key table)
and the public DKIM key retrieved from DNS match.
.SH BATCH (WHOLE KEYTABLE) MODE
When a
.I KeyTable
is configured and none of
.I \-d,
.I \-s
or
.I \-k
is given on the command line, every entry in the key table is tested in
turn rather than a single domain/selector pair.  Each key is checked
exactly as in single-key mode (its public record is retrieved and, where a
key file is named, compared against the private key).  With
.I \-v
a one-line summary reporting the number of keys checked and the pass and
fail counts is printed at the end.
.PP
The exit status summarises the batch: it is
.I EX_OK
(0) only if every key passed, and
.I EX_DATAERR
(65) if any key failed.  This makes the whole-table run suitable for
deployment verification and cron-driven monitoring without having to loop
over domains externally.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I \-d domain
Names the domain in which signing is to be done.  More specifically,
names the domain in which the public key matching the provided private
key will be found.  This parameter must be provided either explicitly,
in the configuration file, or via a KeyTable (see
.I phoenixdkim.conf(5)
for details).
.TP
.I \-k keypath
Specifies the path to the private key file which should be used for
this test.  This parameter is optional.
.TP
.I \-s selector
Names the selector within the specified domain whose public key should
be retrieved and tested, comparing it to the private key if provided.
This parameter must be provided either explicitly, in the configuration
file, or via a KeyTable (see
.I phoenixdkim.conf(5)
for details).
.TP
.I \-v
Increases verbosity.  May be specified multiple times.
.TP
.I \-x conffile
Names a configuration file to be parsed.  See
.I phoenixdkim.conf(5)
for details.  The values used are Domain, Selector, KeyFile, KeyTable,
TrustAnchorFile and ResolverConfig.  The default is
.I /etc/phoenixdkim/phoenixdkim.conf.
.SH NOTES
The test program will also complain if a private key file is readable
by anyone other than the user executing the program.

Both RSA and Ed25519 private keys are supported.
.SH VERSION
This man page covers the version of
.I phoenixdkim-testkey
that shipped with version 1.0.0 of
.I PhoenixDKIM.
